  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">Section 04</div>
    <h2>Consumer Psychology &amp; Learnings</h2>
    <p class="section-intro">What the performance data reveals about how this audience thinks, where they are in their decision journey, and what moves them to act.</p>

    <div class="insight-grid">

      <div class="insight-card">
        <div class="ic-label">Decision state</div>
        <h3>This audience is in a decision loop, not a discovery loop</h3>
        <p>The top-performing copy doesn't educate — it unsticks. "What are you actually waiting for?" assumes the reader already knows about GLP-1s and has been sitting on it. The data confirms this: friction-removal language ("that's the whole risk", "$0 assessment", "5 minutes") outperforms awareness-building copy. The job is not to introduce an idea, it's to give permission to act.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="insight-card">
        <div class="ic-label">Trust barrier</div>
        <h3>Scepticism is an identity, not just an objection</h3>
        <p>"It makes sense to be suspicious" converts because it reflects back how this person sees themselves — as someone who doesn't get fooled. Leading with "you're right to doubt this" is qualitatively different from reassurance. It compliments their judgment before selling to them. Copy that leads with Juniper's credentials or features triggers the exact skepticism it's trying to overcome.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="insight-card">
        <div class="ic-label">System frustration</div>
        <h3>The Canadian healthcare system is a live grievance</h3>
        <p>The GP critique ("10-minute appointments", "told you to eat less and move more") resonates because it's lived experience. Universal healthcare means this audience has had the public system dismiss them, repeatedly. Positioning Juniper as an alternative to a system that has failed them is more emotionally charged than positioning against a competitor.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="insight-card">
        <div class="ic-label">Risk framing</div>
        <h3>Risk mitigation needs to be explicit, not implied</h3>
        <p>The best-performing copy names the risk and shrinks it in one move: "The consultation is free. The quiz is 5 minutes. That's the whole risk." Burying "free assessment" in the CTA is not the same thing. This audience needs the cost of trying to feel genuinely negligible — stated directly, not just structurally available. Risk removal should appear throughout the funnel, not only in the headline.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="insight-card">
        <div class="ic-label">Emotional stage</div>
        <h3>"It's not your fault" validates but doesn't convert</h3>
        <p>Empathy-led copy ("You've done the hard part: realising it's not your fault") drives quiz starts but not purchases. It releases shame and leaves people in a reflective emotional state — but reflection is not the same as readiness. Copy that validates and immediately pivots to action ("here's the one thing you haven't tried yet") is the gap to close.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="insight-card">
        <div class="ic-label">Message timing</div>
        <h3>The "beyond medication" message is mistimed in cold prospecting</h3>
        <p>The high hold rates (34–40%) on "what GLP-1s won't tell you" and "4.5x more weight" copy show deep reading — but no purchases follow. The message creates complexity before the primary decision is made: "do I want to start?". Telling someone the medication alone isn't enough, before they've committed to starting, introduces doubt about the category. This message belongs in retargeting, not cold prospecting.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="insight-card">
        <div class="ic-label">Creative format</div>
        <h3>Authentic UGC stops the scroll better than anything else</h3>
        <p>JUN115 Car Story A has a 48.8% hook rate — nearly half of everyone who sees it stops scrolling. Car Story B drives the highest CTR (2.52%) and best quiz starts in the campaign. Talking-to-camera UGC is outperforming all other formats on attention metrics. This audience trusts real people talking to camera over produced creative.</p>
      </div>

