    <h2>Creative Direction &amp; Feedback</h2>
    <p class="section-intro">Specific feedback on what's working, what to fix, and principles for the next round of creative.</p>

    <div class="feedback-item">
      <div class="fi-tag works">What's working — keep &amp; scale</div>
      <h3>Start inside the reader's head, not inside our product</h3>
      <p>The top-performing copy shares one structural quality: the opening line describes something the reader already feels. "What are you actually waiting for?" names a feeling. "It makes sense to be suspicious" reflects a thought back. This is the test for every new piece of copy: does the first sentence describe something the reader is already thinking, or does it describe something we want them to know? The former converts. The latter doesn't.</p>
      <p>The "what are you waiting for?" body + "Free to See If You Qualify" headline is the benchmark combination: 2.32% CTR, 38.4% hook, $26 CPReg. Every new variant should be compared against this.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="feedback-item">
      <div class="fi-tag works">What's working — replicate the mechanism</div>
      <h3>Name the risk, then collapse it completely</h3>
      <p>"That's the whole risk" is the strongest close in this campaign. It doesn't say "low risk" — it names the specific risk and declares it negligible. This is different from listing features ("$0 assessment, no clinic visit") because it acknowledges the reader's hesitation explicitly before dismissing it.</p>
      <p>Every piece of copy needs a version of this moment before the CTA. Not "free to see if you're eligible" as a throwaway — a direct, named articulation of what the reader is risking by clicking, and why it's nothing.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="feedback-item">
      <div class="fi-tag fix">What to fix — specific issues</div>
      <h3>The feature-led and emoji copy isn't working</h3>
      <p>The "✅ Practitioner support isn't a slogan. It's a person" copy had the worst CTR in the campaign. The problem isn't the emoji alone — it's that the whole piece reads like a product brochure. It opens with our feature, defends it against an objection nobody raised, then lists more features.</p>
      <p>This audience has been sold to before by companies making exactly these claims. When you open with credentials, you're asking them to evaluate you. When you open with their experience, you're asking them to recognise themselves. These are different psychological entry points — one creates resistance, one creates connection.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="feedback-item">
      <div class="fi-tag fix">What to fix — specific issues</div>
      <h3>Strip the biography from the "two kids, full-time job" copy</h3>
      <p>The emotional core of this piece is strong: "at some point you just accepted that this was what life looked like now." That line works for almost everyone in the cohort. The problem is getting there requires reading through a very specific life story that self-selects. Anyone without kids, or who doesn't identify with "zero bandwidth", disengages before they reach it.</p>
      <p>Rewrite starting from the emotional truth: the exhaustion, the self-blame, the resigned acceptance. Let the audience fill in their own biography rather than giving them yours to reject.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="feedback-item">
      <div class="fi-tag fix">What to fix — specific issues</div>
      <h3>The "beyond medication" copy is in the wrong place in the funnel</h3>
      <p>The 34–40% hold rates on "what GLP-1s won't tell you" and the 4.5x stat copy are genuine signals — people are reading deeply. But the message is creating complexity at the wrong moment. If someone hasn't fully committed to starting GLP-1s, telling them "the medication alone isn't enough" introduces doubt about the whole category, not just other providers.</p>
      <p>Commission retargeting versions of these concepts: <em>"You've started looking into this — here's why how you do it matters."</em> That's a completely different frame from trying to convince someone to start. In cold prospecting, these concepts should be reserved for the hold/engagement role while a stronger direct-response close carries the conversion.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="feedback-item">
      <div class="fi-tag direction">Direction for next round</div>
      <h3>Fix the Car Story A edit — the hook is already solved</h3>
      <p>JUN115 Car Story A has a 48.8% hook rate — the best of any ad in this campaign. Nearly half of everyone who sees it stops scrolling. But hold drops to 10.6%, meaning almost everyone leaves within 3–5 seconds. This is not a concept problem, it's an edit problem. Something immediately after the opening visual or first line is losing people.</p>
      <p>Don't brief a new concept here — brief a new cut. Find what's happening at the 3–5 second mark and remove or rework it. The front of this ad is exceptional creative that shouldn't be wasted.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="feedback-item">
      <div class="fi-tag direction">Direction for next round</div>
      <h3>Lean into scepticism as the primary opener</h3>
      <p>The "it makes sense to be suspicious" copy converts well on limited spend and has the right mechanism. Brief three new variations of this structure: acknowledge the earned cynicism, validate it specifically (name what has failed before), then position Juniper as different in one concrete, provable way. The key is that the acknowledgment must feel genuine, not performative — if it reads like a sales technique, it will backfire with exactly this audience.</p>
      <blockquote>"Another weight loss program. You've heard that before. So have we. Here's the one thing that's actually different."</blockquote>
      <p>Test variations that name the specific things that have failed (meal plans, GPs, willpower, calorie counting) to increase recognition before pivoting to the solution.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="feedback-item">
      <div class="fi-tag direction">Direction for next round</div>
      <h3>Build the "System Failed You" pillar into the GP indictment angle</h3>
      <p>The current "System Failed You" ads have a $1,544 CPP — but the strongest headline in the account ("Built for What 10-Minute Appointments Miss") comes from this concept space and drives meaningful quiz starts. The pillar has audience resonance but the conversion close is failing. The GP critique creates anger and recognition; what's missing is the immediate redirect from that anger to the action. The gap is: I'm angry at my GP → what do I do right now? Brief copy that builds the frustration and then closes with total immediacy and simplicity.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Principles summary -->
    <div style="background:#1a1a1a;border-radius:8px;padding:28px;margin-top:8px;">
      <div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:.08em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#888;margin-bottom:14px;">Summary principles for next brief</div>
